choices.text:
that I don’t know what I don’t know.

I don’t know when something is and isn’t appropriate for Laos culture.

As a 30 something year old, if I get it wrong, that’s one thing. If I do something inappropriate as a woman in Laos, especially on a state owned or state run Thai think establishment, I might get it wrong and get fleeced, spit on or perhaps worse.

I can usually pick up cultural cues if I observe or pay close attention, but it’s some crap shoot.

Single white American female at the ready.

An hour later was the end of my road… I get to my destination.

It’s a market you can easily spend time in. Thing is, I’m just here for basic essentials. Same spot, same vendor. I looked through the pantry to see what had been taken or eaten/neglected by the mice and others. When I told him he was out of the stuff, he said a customer might have bought it as well. He’s honest. It’s also possible that some customer said that amount and the vendor sold it (it looked good, nothing bad was on it). But I was skeptical. That happens, so I was happy in any event that he had some, so it made the transaction easier.

In between pointing and speaking actual Lao sentences, I almost know what to do.

But today was like the first stop of our family that did not bear much productivity. They move things and they race around
